In USA, it's not uncommon for people to be unfamiliar with classical music, or to have trouble distinguishing between different Scandinavian countries. However, that doesn't mean that the influence of classical music on electronic music subgenres in these countries should be overlooked.

In the case of dungeon synth, a subgenre of electronic music that originated in the 1980s and 1990s, it's interesting to consider the distinct musical influences that have shaped its development in different parts of Scandinavia.

For example, in Sweden, it's been suggested that the keyboard and organ music of ABBA, the iconic Swedish pop group, had a significant influence on the development of dungeon synth in the country. ABBA's music is known for its catchy and upbeat sound, and it's not surprising that it would have an impact on other musical genres.

On the other hand, in Norway, it's been suggested that the music of composer Grieg had a greater influence on the development of dungeon synth. Grieg was a 19th century Norwegian composer known for his romantic and nationalistic style, and his music often featured prominent piano and orchestral elements.

While these two examples may seem quite different at first glance, it's worth noting that the use of organs and keyboards is a common feature in both ABBA's music and dungeon synth, and it's possible that this shared element contributed to the influence of ABBA's music on Swedish dungeon synth.

Overall, it's fascinating to consider the various musical influences that have shaped the development of different subgenres of electronic music, and how these influences can vary from one country to another.

December's chill is in the air
As the days grow short and the nights grow long
In the darkness, I find solace

A sound that echoes through the ages
A sound that calls to me
From the frozen depths of winter

Like the glistening icicles on the trees

Like the beating of my heart in the cold

And as I listen to the music

Grim was the world and grey last night:
The moon and stars were fled,
The hall was dark without song or light,
The fires were fallen dead.
The wind in the trees was like to the sea,
And over the mountains' teeth
It whistled bitter-cold and free,
As a sword leapt from its sheath.

The lord of snows upreared his head;
His mantle long and pale
Upon the bitter blast was spread
And hung o'er hill and dale.
The world was blind,
the boughs were bent,
All ways and paths were wild:
Then the veil of cloud apart was rent,
And here was born a Child.

The ancient dome of heaven sheer
Was pricked with distant light;
A star came shining white and clear
Alone above the night.
In the dale of dark in that hour of birth
One voice on a sudden sang:
Then all the bells in Heaven and Earth
Together at midnight rang.

Mary sang in this world below:
They heard her song arise
O’er mist and over mountain snow
To the walls of Paradise,
And the tongue of many bells was stirred
in Heaven's towers to ring
When the voice of mortal maid was heard,
That was mother of Heaven's King.

Glad is the world and fair this night
With stars about its head,
And the hall is filled with laughter and light,
And fires are burning red.
The bells of Paradise now ring
With bells of Christendom,
And Gloria, Gloria we will sing
That God on earth is come.

-Tolkien

Dungeon synth is a style of Electronic music that focuses on evoking epic, atmospheric soundscapes associated with fantasy and medieval settings. Artists primarily utilize synthesizers, keyboards, and drum machines to create Ambient and orchestral textures, with vocals, samples, acoustic instruments, and lo-fi production also occasionally employed. Due to its instrumental nature, dungeon synth musicians concentrate on storytelling through music and create specific sceneries often inspired by mythology, literature of fantasy writers such as J.R.R. Tolkien, video games, and tabletop RPGs like Dungeons & Dragons. The term was coined on March 17th, 2011, in Andrew Werdna's first post on Dungeon Synth Blog, where he described it as "the sound of the ancient crypt."

posts.com:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ytNp0gikre0
Early influences of the genre include Berlin School acts such as Tangerine Dream and Klaus Schulze creating layered, synthesizer-led textures inspired by space and futurism. Jim Kirkwood took these hypnotic soundscapes and used them to produce fantasy-oriented atmospheres. Another wave of influence came from the Neoclassical Darkwave sound of Dead Can Dance, who developed their compositions using synths and drum machines. Dark Ambient and Martial Industrial were also important influences, as plenty of early examples of dungeon synth were guided by those styles.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=85I6tnjsb9I
The first dungeon synth artists emerged in the early-mid 1990s in the wake of the Norwegian Black Metal scene. Mortiis started his solo career after he departed from Emperor and embraced simply-produced, medieval-esque compositions. Varg Vikernes often utilized ambient/dungeon synth interludes on Burzum records, and after his imprisonment, he released his two "prison albums," Dauði Baldrs and Hliðskjálf, which were recorded using a synthesizer and a tape recorder. Other significant projects from the first era include Depressive Silence, who dabbled in ethereal, lush, and lo-fi soundscapes, and Summoning, who accentuated their Symphonic Black Metal sound with keyboards and drum machines.

In the 2000s, dungeon synth experienced a decline, where acts discontinued or went in different directions with their style. The genre began regaining interest in the early 2010s, with blogs and sites such as Andrew Werdna's Dungeon Synth Blog and the Dungeon Synth Archives Youtube channel introducing the genre to new listeners. Werdna's Blog in particular helped establish a more formal description of its sound. Projects which contributed to the revival wave, such as Erang, Lord Lovidicus, and Fief, were inspired by the 1990s acts, while Bandcamp became the successor to the tape trading community. Due to its rising popularity in the late 2010s and 2020s, dungeon synth artists began experimenting with creating different, more specific moods with Winter Synth (Yearner, Inoriand) exploring cold soundscapes while Comfy Synth (Grandma's Cottage, Earthencloak) delved into cozy, nostalgic atmospheres, dropping the epic aesthetic.

Probably because you felt good now and then which inspired your music. That's the ideal IMO. I used to be into a lot of sad music, but now I see a lot of that stuff as kinda self-indulgent. Of course a little bit of sadness is fine, it's classy even. But if you're making entire albums or careers out of being suicidal or being a fuck up then something is wrong desu. Good art should encourage you to live, if music just makes you feel weird or empty or enables some negative trait about yourself, it's misguided.

There was this one very downer album I used to love, the lead singer killed herself, and at times I fantasized about killing myself to it. Like somehow it would have given my life "meaning". In retrospect it was so ridiculous. I'm not saying life is a gift or anything, but suicide and misery has no deeper meaning, pretending it does is one big coping mechanism. This describes my position really well, I think. I'm typically pretty modest and brutally self-critical about this, but upon some sober reflection, I know that I'm relatively talented. I really want nothing more than to be able to spend as much of my time as possible writing and recording music.

I'm incredibly self-critical and particular when it comes to my output however. I've spent the past three years working on an album which I've more or less obsessed over; the few I've shown it to have expressed to me how much they've enjoyed it -- at times, I've been variously proud of it, or have thought it's total shit. I waver back and forth on my opinion of my own music, despite knowing on some basic level that it's, at the very least, okay. I have many opinions on how I think an album ought to be structured and presented.. one of my biggest artistic issues however is an inability to stick to a single concept for too long. To be clear, I have a cohesive, 16 track album, just sitting around, doing nothing; I just no longer find it worthy of release since my interests have more or less moved elsewhere. Working entirely solo doesn't help either; I speak to nobody close to me in real life about my music - it feels passé.

I don't know; sometimes I think that some of my work may be capable of attaining "cult" status under the right circumstances, and other times (which occur more often, recently) I'm convinced they're just delusions of grandeur, and I need to come back to earth.

For reference, a demo off the unreleased album:

And the sort of stuff I'm working on now:

>>114184516
some cool sound design in this, you are talented. there are some mix issues that i probably wouldn't be able to describe without sitting down with you and looking at the project itself. the percussion feels weak; part of the weakness is in the mixing, another part is in the arrangement/stylistic choices. a sampled break would do wonders for the tune; when working entirely synths, tempering the synthetic nature with the character of live percussion can really do wonders. as for the synths, it feels like there's some gnarly resonance in the mid-high region. it's really, really tough to mix an entirely-synth track well. judicious use of eq and bell filters to make each synth track occupy its own distinct place in the mix could be useful. panning is also a hidden dimension through which space can be carved out. pic related; it's from an ancient textbook on mixing, but a useful way to think about space in a mix; 3 axes: volume, frequency, and stereo field. tldr, would focus on mixing fundamentals: eq and parallel compression. good track.

anyone with even the slightest hint of an inclination towards an engineering mindset would immediately be able to tell you that that's a nearly intractable problem. think about, in the ideal, best conditions, how something like that might work. what assumptions would the system need to make about your intent with the song? assuming it can make those assumptions, how is it able to determine what tracks are actually what? (way less possible in the 90s than today.) i'm assuming your father is not a dummy, and there's probably a misunderstanding/miscommunication.

i suppose he could be talking about a system which, given raw, unnormalized tracks, normalizes them to a similar RMS or LUFS value. that certainly would have been possible, but probably would not have yielded listenable or good results, and is hardly "mixing" in the sense it's commonly understood.

Mutes at the bridge are intended for extra thumpy dead string kinda sound used in motown and reggae type songs. The Prophet is the hypothesis, the utopia, the still confused form of things that are not, sketched out in an extravagant sketch. >>114227761
Classical music is like a fine watch, everything needs to fit together perfectly or the watch won't tick. Markings are more of a command rather than suggestion and come with their own period correct interpretations. For example you might play legato in say a Brahms piece more heavy and connected whereas in a Mozart piece you'll still have some separation. Romantic and modern is when your technical playing may get more of a challenge as composers were really experimenting pushing the limits of tonality, Brahms sure loved his poly-rhythms too.
Baroque is a lot more fluid with no thematic juxtaposition but more ornamental. Not a keyboardist though so I can't really go more in depth on the nuances for those instruments.

>Chapter 2 - Wagner, Nietzsche, and the Polemics of Opera
HAHAHA LOL I remember this. Literally written by a Offenbach fanboy with a raging hatred for Wagner. Just take this example:

>Thirteen years later, Offenbach created the first version of Orphée aux enfers, whose climactic orgy seems to say to Wagner “You called that a bacchanal? This is what a bacchanal should be!” Wagner’s inhibition in portraying unbridled sensuality was also noted by Charles Baudelaire, who, in a review of Lohengrin, complained that, although Wagner loved feudal pomp, enthusiastic crowds and “human electricity,” he “has not represented here the turbulence that in a case like this would be manifested by a plebeian [roturière] mob. Even the apex of his most violent tumult expresses nothing but the delirium of people who are used to the rules of etiquette … Its liveliest intoxication still maintains the rhythm of decency.”

It's impossible for the author not to have deliberately misrepresented Baudelaire's statement as a criticism since he quotes it directly from the source. In the original context it was a complement:

>One would say that Wagner loves with a predilection feudal pomp, Homeric assemblies where lies an accumulation of vital force, enthusiastic crowds, reservoir of human electricity, from which the heroic style springs with natural impetuosity. The wedding music and the epithalamium of Lohengrin make a worthy counterpart to the introduction of the guests to the Wartburg in Tannhäuser, perhaps even more majestic and more vehement. However, the master, always full of taste and attentive to nuances, has not represented here the turbulence that in a similar case would be manifested by a plebeian crowd. Even at the apex of its most violent tumult, the music expresses only the delirium of people accustomed to the rules of etiquette; it is a court that enjoys itself, and its liveliest intoxication still keeps the rhythm of decency.

England fell hard for rock and roll though. It took them a while to be able to replicate it convincingly, at least on a mainstream record, but the disenfranchised youth of postwar Britain understandably took to that sound very keenly, and local scenes sprung up almost overnight. They met not have had the racial or ethnic connections but they still had just awful slums and street culture whose members could identify with the raw soul of rock. There’s this quip I heard in some interview that I always remember, that the English knew they’d officially inherited rock and roll when the Little Richard version of Tutti Frutti became a hit in the UK while the Pat Boone version outsold it in the US.

Maybe you had to live in New York at a certain impressionable age and read a now defunct lefty weekly newspaper to have grown up with him, but I have always enjoyed Christgau, even though I wholeheartedly disagree with him about a lot of stuff.

To "get" Christgau, you have to first put him into the context of his time. He began writing music articles in 1967 (one of his first was a notorious piece about the Monterey Pop Festival in which he very loquaciously elucidated the square-ish young academic's view of the beginnings of the rock and roll counterculture, and infamously referred to Jimi Hendrix (making his US debut) as a 'psychedelic Uncle Tom", words he has come to regret).

In 1967, there was barely a such thing as rock music criticism. Insofar as it existed at all, it can be traced all the way back to 1966. Before that, rock and roll was purely kid's stuff as far as newspapers were concerned. There were no rock magazines, unless Seventeen and Tiger Beat count, both aimed at teenaged girls. News coverage of rock music was mostly limited to screaming teenaged girls at Beatles concerts, where the screaming was the story and the music was inaudible.

To serious rock and roll musicologists, 1966 was a watershed year; as far as "exciting and new and not just for kids anymore" was concerned, 1966 was the game changer. Bob Dylan had fully converted to rock music, bands like The Beatles, The Byrds, The Rolling Stones, The Beach Boys and others were writing music that appealed to the college-age crowd (i.e. Baby Boomers) and offered a newfound maturity in lyrical content while pushing previously unimagined boundaries sonically.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
San Francisco Chronicle critic Ralph J. Gleason was one of the first music critics to review rock music seriously, in 1965, and he heavily covered the San Francisco scene, giving it national prominence. Richard Goldstein had a column called Pop Eye, which treated rock music with sophistication; it began in 1966. Crawdaddy, the very first rock magazine, launched in 1966. Among its contributors were much of the nucleus of the "new rock criticism", including Jon Landau, Sandy Pearlman and Richard Meltzer.

In 1967, both the Summer of Love happened and Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band was released which Goldstein panned, incidentally. Monterey Pop happens. Suddenly, hip, young, educated adults are into rock music in a big way, and a whole cottage industry of rock criticism sprouted up. Rolling Stone was launched in 1967. At various times, early rock critics such as Dave Marsh and later Lester Bangs picked up checks there.

It was this milieu that Christgau got his gig writing the Consumer Guide for the Village Voice. A monthly encapsulated rock album review column that spanned across all rock genres and included some interesting music at the fringes of rock was a wholly novel concept. Due to the limitations of space in the paper, his capsule reviews had to be very brief, and he often resorted to shorthand in capturing fairly insightful descriptions of 20+ albums at a time. His amusingly academic wordplay, his generally decent-family-man perspective, his firmly ingrained from-the-streets-of-New-York lefty worldview, and his general adventurousness in following his love of rock music into unexpected byways (which led him into African music ever since he heard The Indestructible Beat of Soweto in 1982) all made him fun to read. The concept of the Consumer Guide has been lost in the digital archive age. You had x amount of dollars to spend on records each month, so where should you allocate those funds? The reviews were never meant to be taken outside of that.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
He was useful in that he let you know what was out there, and he gave honest appraisals. Often his appraisal was idiotic, but at least he had an ideology about rock music and pop music. He wasn't a hack.

Generally, he likes classic 60's rock, is leery of folk, embraces rap and hip hop, loves African music, never really understood heavy metal, has always given indie music wide coverage, even if he loved some of it and hated some of it. He never had much use of prog-rock, is only swayed by art-rock if it lives up to its pretenses, came to appreciate country music later in life, and is a sucker for young, female pop singers as long as they aren't too vapid. He did indeed miss the boat on Black Sabbath, but the dummies over at Rolling Stone hated them too Only Lester Bangs stood up for them.

Knowing his preferences and biases, one can read between the lines and know if his opinion on a particular album is going to be insightful or not. I will say that Christgau talked me into listening to a lot of artists I never would have otherwise tried, and whom I still cherish now. And that's the whole purpose of rock criticism, isn't it?

I will say that his best Consumer Guides were from 1969 until 1990. After that, he got too selective in what he'd review, which meant he got a lot more idiosyncratic. I like reading his reviews of artists I know, and he listens to very few of them these days.

I acknowledge that if you simply come across random reviews of his, he may come across as a supercilious idiot. I won't defend his politics, but he would be happy to. He is sometimes very astute and nuanced in his thinking, even if he comes across as an overly academic, pseudo hip (much of that is meant with irony), musically ignorant socialist at times.

He was...how do the kids say it these days?...a man of his time. Now, he's just old. But he's a decent fellow; he is what he is.

>>114224457

I think the first record is too difficult a listen to be more than a contrarian choice for the best- you have to already have acquired a strong taste for that kind of abrasive - stuff like early La Dispute or As Cities Burn is a lot more enjoyable without sacraficing songcraft or technicality.

Three Cheers is where the band reaches their stride, and when the highest highs of their songwriting was reached, but to say that the Black Parade is bad when these records are cut from the same cloth is disingenuous. There are no really weak tracks on The Black Parade, Teenagers being the contender for worst, but it's still a decent song. Three Cheers sort of has a weak patch near the end, it's less consistent. The fact that the Black Parade is accessible (again, so is Three Cheers) or that it seems to take influence from bands like Aerosmith with some of the slow songs doesn't make it worse, necessarily.

On that note, the theatrical aspects are why I compared it to >>114223697 Say Anything or that it fit in with records like American Idiot. It's not that MCR is a pop punk band, but that there is serious overlap in the target audience- it represented a trend for increasing effort in Pop Punk to ascend beyond the alleged shallow vapid formulaic stereotypes of the genre, and of musical theatre influence percolating in. This period also saw Marianas Trench's Masterpiece Theatre, which has Queen influence and big medleys, or Blink 182 trying to grow up on their Self-Titled. Bands were suddenly making front to back albums and crafting longer songs, or slow songs that weren't the one acoustic song on the album.

T. Pop punk historian

Now that the dust has settled I have a few reasons to criticize the Black Parade- The End or Mama are a bit over the top, for example, especially the production and all the instruments used- and often especially in Rawk less is more. So the Black Parade is an indicator of that trend. I haven't even really listened to Danger Days, but I think a lot of the bands in the scene should have stuck with guitars, and that's why generally the first 3 or so albums by bands in the scene are considered the best to fans of the genre (you could call them puritans). This pattern happened to so many bands. Fall Out Boy, Say Anything, Marianas Trench, All Time Low, Relient K, the list is endless. I always check out the Blackpink releases (it's not hard, they're like 20 mins long at best) and songs on them are always confusing, uninspired, painfully oversung or downright hilarious (usually all of the above).

This particular record's saving grace is the song "Yeah Yeah Yeah", a not particularly groundbreaking, but nice throwback-y deep cut, which only stands out because it is not oversung and chock full of last decade's rejected lyrics.

The rest is, of course, unlistenable. I dare you to listen to it with a straight face.

Which just goes to show that the producers or company employees or whoever writes their music and handles their public persona, never had any concrete vision for these girls. They just throw together any old cr*p out of the complete hack's guide to bland songwriting every couple of years and hope for the best, and the worst part is that these girls can't even perform these songs particularly well.

What a load of wasted potential. Or maybe it isn't so wasted, since they are technically successful and make money, but at least it is a waste of storage space, CDs, etc. And of course a waste of time to give this any listens, unless you are a die-hard stan and you want to get hyped for your girls.

From Mark Langan

"Out of my friends, I was the guy who they always thought would never have a chance of getting clean because I was so maniacal in my approach.

"I would have climbed Mount Everest for drugs. I was always trying to kick. Layne was a magical person who was also hellbent on doing drugs until he died.

"The first time I saw him after I'd gotten clean, I'd been clean a year. I'm pretty sure that [Alice in Chains guitarist] Jerry [Cantrell] and [bassist] Mike Inez flew me up to Seattle because they were unable to get into his house. He had a camera and lived in the penthouse of this condo.

"So whenever anybody from that camp would come to see him, he would just ignore it. Jerry and Mike knew that when he saw me, he would let me in.

"I went along with that, and I also wanted him to see that I was clean, that it was possible to get clean, that his prediction that I would never be able to do it had failed. [Laughs] Hopefully, maybe, it would give him the idea that he, himself, could do it. But he didn't want to do it.

"When I got there, I said, 'Hey, man, it's been a while. I've been clean for more than 12 months.' And he was like, 'No, you weren't, man. You just left, like, two months ago.' His sense of time had warped. And he wasn't buying the truth from me.

"I remember him saying at that point, 'I always just keep thinking I'm gonna get that same feeling I got the first time again.' And, dude, I never got that first feeling again after the first time I ever did dope.

"I immediately had to do five times more to even get close to it. So for me, that was an impossibility, but that was his obsession."

posts.com: It's not inherently a bad thing, it depends on the individual person. You're right, you used to have to have a guru, lucked into the right friends, etc. to find the real shit. The internet flipped all of that, and you're six degrees of bacon away from finding anything to lead you down rabbit holes to anywhere now. For me, few friends and none of them into music that did it for me, it was a boon. I spent years digging around and listening, but I still had no social media and no friends to look cool with, so it was all about love of the sounds and respect for the artistry. I was getting into the music for the right reasons, basically. In the social media age, finding all of these 'hidden gems' that aren't hidden seems largely a social thing or competition even. Not the right reasons.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
I think the real problem is that it's hard for newcomers to appreciate the evolution of a genre, and it's hard to draw lines of where a sound came from or what is mandatory listening.

For example if I like Deerhunter but never got into Animal Collective and feel no need to, and I may even be the local "expert" on neo-psychedelia but if the production or tropes of the past (even if they seem the same to some) have some sort of difference in "vibe," that is, the subjective experience of the listener, it just isn't compelling enough to get someone to put the so called "original" on a pedestal that connoiseurs might believe it deserves.

And this is exactly how I feel about Slint as well, in that the production is abraisive, and the kind of "post rock" I prefer is more cold, ambient, and psychedelic, such as the more abstract Deerhunter pieces.

I think the democratization of information should be a good thing as long as newcomers have a bit of humility. AI recommendations will make the scene even more fragmented unless there are touchstones "out there" in the collective unconscious or the same exploratory paths become excessively trodden.

I think there are some interesting things coming out of the fusion of hiphop and core genres, and lo-fi noisy stuff like Weatherday but maybe I'm naive thinking that stuff is new.

The monetary side of music has taken a hit for sure because the internet and how everyone thinks content should be free, which is making advertising the only source of revenue beyond subscription services. The flood of content is a mixed bag for artists because millions of people like me were able to make a professionally produced album and put it online where exactly 20 people will ever hear it. An ocean sunfish fry has a better chance of growing to dinner table size than the average musician has of making even enough money to pay for their instruments, recording, and gas.

On that note, the amount of "content" is pretty much infinite if you know how to find what you're looking for or willing to give something new a shot.

The best 70's rock album is obviously Led Zeppelin IV, or ZOSO, or "untitled," or whatever you want to call it before that argument kicks in.

The first two songs, Black Dog and Rock & Roll, are the musical blueprint for heavy rock for the next two decades. Stairway To Heaven, two songs later, is the most-requested song of all time. When The Levee Breaks, the closer, is widely considered by fellow musicians to be the "heaviest" song ever. It was the game-changer for AOR radio, which was the equivalent of the internet in the early 70's. There has never been an album to equal its impact and there never will be.

anon please practice with a tuner, you can become in-tune very quickly but you need to do long notes with a tuner. for everyone in this thread who wants to acquire a good sound: look up "high tones eugene rousseau pdf", click the first link, start doing the exercises, and do an exercise where you start with the most beautiful note you can currently play and try to get an identical sound on all notes on the instrument, starting with the closest ones a half-step away. the note should take 8 beats of 60 bpm. then spend the rest of the practice session doing whatever you want. when you lift other saxophonists, lift their timbre as well, not just the notes they're playing.
